On National Agriculture Day, President Joseph R. Biden Jr. recognizes the important contributions of farmers, ranchers, foresters, farmworkers, and other agricultural stewards to the nation. He acknowledges the role of the agriculture sector in sustainable land management, animal and plant health, food supply, and economic development in rural America. The president highlights the efforts of workers and leaders in the agriculture sector during the COVID-19 pandemic to ensure a stable food supply. He emphasizes the importance of programs that address nutrition insecurity and commits to advancing racial equity and addressing the harmful effects of systemic racism in agriculture. President Biden also pledges to tackle the climate crisis and highlights the critical role of farmers, ranchers, and foresters in combating climate change. Finally, he proclaims March 23, 2021, as National Agriculture Day and calls upon all Americans to appreciate and support those working in the agriculture sector.